**Bug 1 — The Auth Loop**

When someone clicks "Sign in with Google," Google handles the login and sends them back to your app. Your backend receives that, creates a session token, and then redirects the user to a specific page on your frontend to complete the handoff — `/auth/token-bridge`.

The problem: that page doesn''t exist in your frontend. So the user lands on a broken URL, the token gets thrown away, and the app sends them back to the landing page like they were never logged in. That''s the loop.

The fix is just building that one missing page and adding it to the router.

---

**Bug 2 — The Silent Failure**

When you''re chatting with Atlas and something goes wrong on the backend — like Claude''s API throws an error — your backend is supposed to tell the frontend "hey, something failed." 

The way it works: the backend sends a signal called `event: error`. The frontend listens for that signal and shows you an error message.

The problem: when something actually fails, the backend sends `event: done` instead of `event: error`. The frontend hears "done" and thinks the response just finished normally — with no content. So you see a blank chat bubble. No error message. No indication anything went wrong. It just silently fails.

The fix is changing one word in the backend code so it sends the right signal.

---

Both are small fixes. Neither requires redesigning anything. Want me to go ahead and build them?', NULL, NULL, '2026-06-15T09:58:14.595Z', 9960, 53239, 336, '0.16476', 'completed', 'Sure. Plain English.', NULL, NULL) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;

