3. Created a lookup index to support the 60-second title dedup window.
4. Backfilled: archived older duplicates by `(project_id, title)` using `status = ''archived''` (the only transition allowed by the `entries_enforce_lock` trigger).

What we still need to do (backend code — this task):
Add a two-layer dedup guard inside the `POST /projects/:projectId/entries` handler, BEFORE the existing `db.insert(entriesTable).values({...}).returning()` call.

Layer 1 — Idempotency by source message: if the request body includes `sourceMessageId`, look up an existing entry with the same `user_id` + `source_message_id`. If found, return it instead of inserting.

Layer 2 — 60-second title window: look up an existing entry with the same `user_id` + `project_id` + trimmed `title`, created in the last 60 seconds, where `status <> ''archived''`. If found, return it instead of inserting.

If neither matches, perform the existing insert, but also write `sourceMessageId` into the new row.

Required supporting changes:
- The Drizzle schema for `entriesTable` (likely in `artifacts/api-server/src/db/schema.ts`) must declare `sourceMessageId: uuid("source_message_id")` if it isn''t there yet.
- The Zod request-body schema for this route must accept `sourceMessageId: z.string().uuid().optional()`.

Why: without this guard, rapid double-clicks or retried network calls from the frontend create duplicate ledger rows. The DB unique index protects against same-message duplicates; the 60s window catches user-initiated repeats.

