 rather than ask you questions about your own product, and identified that live app access (a staging URL or walkthrough) would give me the accuracy you need to trust my evaluations. The next step is for you to provide either a live link to test Compani or walk me through the actual user experience so I can assess the real state of the app rather than the code''s intent.","createdAt":"2026-06-03T01:08:51.191Z","retrievalCount":28,"lastRetrievedAt":"2026-06-14T19:55:44.832Z"},{"tier":3,"text":"[Session Jun 3, 2026] We discussed the Compani app''s readiness for launch and the effectiveness of its onboarding flow. You pushed back on my initial assessments for being too passive and document-focused rather than code-focused, establishing that I should proactively read the codebase and give you direct observations rather than deferring to files you haven''t reviewed. We identified that better assessment of the app requires either live app access (a staging URL or walkthrough of what you''re seeing) or you articulating what specific areas you want me to evaluate, since code reading alone has gaps compared to runtime experience. The logical next step is for you to either share a staging link so I can see the app running, or tell me which specific feature or flow you want me to dig into first in the codebase with concrete findings ready.","createdAt":"2026-06-03T02:36:36.735Z","retrievalCount":28,"lastRetrievedAt":"2026-06-14T19:55:44.832Z"},{"tier":3,"text":"[Session Jun 3, 2026] We discussed the Compani app''s user readiness and identified a critical gap in how I''m assessing it: I was deferring to documentation you hadn''t read instead of directly analyzing the codebase itself, and I was making assumptions about the onboarding flow without understanding that rituals and setup steps are sequenced over time rather than all front-loaded on day one. We decided that to give you better, more proactive assessments going forward, I need either live app access (a staging URL or walkthrough) so I can see the actual user experience in the browser, or you describing what you''re seeing as you use it, since the gap between code intent and runtime behavior is where real issues hide. The next step is for you to either share a working version of Compani or walk me through a fresh user signup so I can assess the actual day-one experience and give you concrete feedback on whether it''s truly user-ready.","createdAt":"2026-06-03T03:27:10.773Z","retrievalCount":28,"lastRetrievedAt":"2026-06-14T19:55:44.832Z"},{"tier":3,"text":"[Session Jun 3, 2026] We discussed the Compani app''s readiness for launch and specifically debated whether the onboarding flow exists and how it''s structured; you clarified that onboarding components are spread across time with progressive disclosure rather than stacked on day one, and I acknowledged I''d been reading code passively rather than actively assessing what''s actually there. The decision made was that I should shift to proactive analysis of the codebase itself rather than deferring to files you haven''t read or asking you questions about your own app. The logical next step is for you to either provide a staging URL so I can see the app running, or describe what you''re actually seeing on screen so I can give you assessment based on real user experience rather than code interpretation alone.","createdAt":"2026-06-03T10:47:50.884Z","retrievalCount":27,"lastRetrievedAt":"2026-06-14T19:55:44.832Z"},{"tier":3,"text":"[Session Jun 3, 2026] We discussed the Compani app''s readiness for launch, with you pushing back on my initial vague assessment and correctly pointing out that I should be reading the actual codebase rather than deferring to documents you haven''t reviewed. Through that conversation, we identified that the onboarding exists and is intelligently sequenced over time rather than front-loaded, and we clarified that I was confusing \"exists\" with \"is optimized.\" We decided that to give you better, more proactive assessments going forward, I need either live app access (a staging URL to click through) or you walking me through what you''re actually seeing on screen, since the gap between code and runtime is where real issues surface.","createdAt":"2026-06-03T11:03:20.187Z","retrievalCount":23,"lastRetrievedAt":"2026-06-14T19:55:44.832Z"},{"tier":3,"text":"[Session Jun 3, 2026] We discussed the Compani app''s readiness for users and identified a critical gap in my assessment approach — I was deferring to documentation and asking questions instead of actively analyzing the codebase itself, which frustrated your trust in my role as a technical partner. We decided that to give you sharper, more proactive answers about features like onboarding flow, chat experience, and user journey, I need either live app access (a staging URL or walkthrough of what you''re seeing) or you to describe the actual running experience, since code alone doesn''t reveal where execution differs from intent. The next step is for you to either share access to a running version of Compani or describe what a new user actually sees when they sign up, so I can ground my assessments in reality rather than assumptions.","createdAt":"2026-06-03T11:24:48.643Z","retrievalCount":23,"lastRetrievedAt":"2026-06-14T19:55:44.832Z"},{"tier":3,"text":"[Session Jun 4, 2026] We discussed the Compani app''s readiness for launch and identified a critical gap in my ability to assess it effectively — I can read the codebase but lack visibility into the actual running application and user experience. You established that I should be proactively analyzing files rather than deferring to documentation, and we clarified that the onboarding is well-designed with progressive disclosure rather than a heavy front-loaded flow. The next step is for you to provide either live app access (a staging URL) or a walkthrough of what users actually see when they interact with Compani, which will let me give you accurate assessments instead of