INSERT INTO "projects" ("id", "user_id", "name", "description", "status", "memory", "preview_url", "github_token", "linked_repo", "node_state", "push_history", "last_handover_at", "last_handover_hash", "created_at", "updated_at", "entity_type", "last_opened_at", "linked_repos", "surface_mode", "shape", "working_title", "committed_at") VALUES (31, 1, 'Axiom-Atlas', NULL, 'committed', '{"v":2,"entries":[{"tier":3,"text":"[Session May 27, 2026] You discussed authentication loop problems in the Atlas frontend repository, specifically a Google OAuth flow that redirects back to the landing page with a missing or \"null\" session, and identified the service worker and token exchange pattern as likely culprits—the SW may still be intercepting routes it shouldn''t, or the backend redirect after Google auth completion isn''t reaching the `/auth-callback` endpoint as expected. You decided to gather information from Lovable about what they said regarding the auth state, and Atlas offered to scan the codebase to identify the exact failure point in the token exchange chain. The logical next step was to retrieve that Lovable documentation or conversation, confirm whether the backend is actually redirecting to `/auth-callback` with a valid token, and test the service worker''s current route skipping rules to isolate which part of the flow is breaking.","createdAt":"2026-05-27T21:59:53.361Z","retrievalCount":35,"lastRetrievedAt":"2026-06-16T09:50:02.364Z"},{"tier":3,"text":"[Session Jun 5, 2026] We discussed the Google OAuth authentication loop in Axiom-Atlas, identified that the backend redirects to `/auth/token-bridge?token=xxx` but that route is missing from the frontend router, and established that this missing route is why users loop back to the landing page instead of exchanging the token for a session. We then switched context to atlas-idk repo and attempted to read `src/hooks/useNexusChatStream.ts` to diagnose an isPending reset logic issue, but hit a file access failure due to either branch mismatch or token permissions. The next step is to verify the correct branch and token permissions for atlas-idk, then fetch and fix the useNexusChatStream.ts file to address the isPending reset bug.","createdAt":"2026-06-05T01:41:15.925Z","retrievalCount":27,"lastRetrievedAt":"2026-06-16T09:50:02.364Z"},{"tier":3,"text":"[Session Jun 5, 2026] We diagnosed the Google OAuth authentication loop in Axiom-Atlas where the backend redirects to `/auth/token-bridge?token=xxx` but that route doesn''t exist in the frontend Router, causing the token exchange to fail and users to bounce back to landing. We then pivoted to examining the Nexus chat stream error handling and discovered a critical mismatch: when Claude''s API throws an error, the backend sends `event: done` instead of `event: error`, so the frontend never displays failure states to the user. The next step is to modify `nexus.ts` to send `event: error` with the error summary when `stream.on(\"error\")` fires, then update the frontend stream listener to handle that event and display the error message properly.","createdAt":"2026-06-05T01:48:55.245Z","retrievalCount":24,"lastRetrievedAt":"2026-06-16T09:50:02.364Z"},{"tier":3,"text":"[Session Jun 5, 2026] We diagnosed a Google OAuth authentication loop in Axiom-Atlas where the backend redirects to `/auth/token-bridge?token=xxx` after successful Google login, but that route doesn''t exist in the frontend Router, causing the token exchange to fail and users to bounce back to the landing page unauthenticated. We also identified a critical mismatch in the streaming error handling: when Claude''s API throws an error, the backend sends `event: done` instead of `event: error`, so the frontend never renders the failure state to the user. The next step is to add the missing `/auth/token-bridge` route to `App.tsx` and modify `nexus.ts` to send `event: error` on stream failures so the frontend can properly catch and display error states.","createdAt":"2026-06-05T02:28:14.075Z","retrievalCount":24,"lastRetrievedAt":"2026-06-16T09:50:02.364Z"},{"tier":3,"text":"[Session Jun 5, 2026] We diagnosed a Google OAuth authentication loop in Axiom-Atlas where the backend redirects to `/auth/token-bridge?token=xxx` after successful Google sign-in, but that route doesn''t exist in the frontend router, causing the token exchange to fail and the user to land back on the landing page unauthenticated. We also identified a stream error handling mismatch in nexus.ts where real model failures send `event: done` instead of `event: error`, so the frontend never displays an error message to the user. The next step is to add the missing `/auth/token-bridge` route to App.tsx and fix the stream error event type in nexus.ts to properly propagate failures to the client.","createdAt":"2026-06-05T04:11:45.470Z","retrievalCount":24,"lastRetrievedAt":"2026-06-16T09:50:02.364Z"},{"tier":3,"text":"[Session Jun 6, 2026] We discussed a Google OAuth authentication loop in Axiom-Atlas where the backend redirects to `/auth/token-bridge?token=xxx` but that route doesn''t exist in the frontend router, causing the token exchange to fail and users to land back on the landing page unauthenticated. We identified that the root cause was a missing route in `App.tsx` and that Claude had corrected my earlier incorrect analysis about a missing `/auth-callback` route, which taught us the importance of reading actual code rather than assuming patterns. The logical next step is to add the `/auth/token-bridge` route to the frontend router and confirm the token exchange flow completes end-to-end, then verify the session cookie is properly set and readable by the frontend.","createdAt":"2026-06-06T14:53:36.118Z","retrievalCount":24,"lastRetrievedAt":"2026-06-16T09:50:02.364Z"},{"tier":3,"text":"[Session Jun 6, 2026] I''m here and ready.\n\nWe identified that when the Claude API stream fails in `nexus.ts`, the `failStream()` function sends `event: done` to the client, but `useAtlasStream.ts` on the frontend only displays error states when it receives `event: error` — so real failures show up as silent blank bubbles instead of error messages to the user.\n\nTo fix this properly, I need to know: do you want me to change `nexus.ts` to send `event: error` on failure, update `useAtlasStream.ts` to handle `event: done` as a potential error state, or do both?","createdAt":"2026-06-06T23:48:18.938Z","retrievalCount":23,"lastRetrievedAt":"2026-06-16T09:50:02.364Z"},{"tier":2,"text":"Jochanae catches pattern-matching vs actual code reading immediately and calls it out directly — always read the actual file before making claims, never reason from generic patterns","createdAt":"2026-06-07T21:35:10.820Z","retrievalCount":22,"lastRetrievedAt":"2026-06-16T09:50:02.364Z"},{"tier":3,"text":"[Session Jun 7, 2026] Session Summary: We discussed the silent failure bug in your Atlas streaming architecture where Claude model errors trigger `failStream()` sending `event: done` instead of `event: error`, causing the frontend to display blank bubbles instead of error messages. You provided the relevant code snippets from `nexus.ts` showing how `stream.on(\"error\")` handles failures. The decision made was to identify which layer needs patching—either the backend''s `failStream` logic to send the correct event type, the frontend''s `useAtlasStream.ts` error handling to catch `done` events with error metadata, or both. The next step is to confirm your preferred fix location and implement the patch to ensure users see meaningful error feedback when the model call fails.","createdAt":"2026-06-07T21:36:43.226Z","retrievalCount":22,"lastRetrievedAt":"2026-06-16T09:50:02.364Z"},{"tier":3,"text":"[Session Jun 8, 2026] **Session Summary:**\n\nWe diagnosed a critical silent failure bug in the Atlas streaming architecture where Claude model errors on the backend trigger `failStream()` to send `event: done` instead of `event: error`, causing the frontend `useAtlasStream.ts` to render a blank message bubble instead of displaying the error to the user. The root cause lies in the mismatch between what `stream.on(\"error\")` calls on the backend (failStream with status \"failed\") and what the frontend actually listens for (only `event: error` triggers error UI). The immediate next step is to patch either the backend `nexus.ts` to send the correct event type or the frontend hook to handle `event: done` with failed status, then test the fix end-to-end to confirm users see actual error messages instead of silent failures.","createdAt":"2026-06-08T03:56:28.573Z","retrievalCount":22,"lastRetrievedAt":"2026-06-16T09:50:02.364Z"},{"tier":3,"text":"[Session Jun 8, 2026] **Session Summary**\n\nWe diagnosed a silent failure bug in your streaming chat implementation where Claude model errors trigger `failStream()` on the backend, which sends `event: done` instead of `event: error`, causing the frontend to display a blank bubble instead of an error message to the user. You provided the relevant code snippets from `nexus.ts` showing that `stream.on(\"error\")` calls `failStream()` with a status parameter, but the frontend listener in `useAtlasStream.ts` only renders error UI when it receives `event: error`. The fix requires either modifying `nexus.ts` to send the correct event type on failure, or updating the frontend to handle the `done` event as a failure state when it contains error metadata. The next step is to decide which layer to patch and apply the fix to GitHub.","createdAt":"2026-06-08T07:30:14.297Z","retrievalCount":22,"lastRetrievedAt":"2026-06-16T09:50:02.364Z"},{"tier":3,"text":"[Session Jun 8, 2026] **Session Summary:**\n\nWe diagnosed a silent failure bug in your Atlas streaming pipeline where Claude model errors trigger `failStream()` to send `event: done` instead of `event: error`, causing the frontend to render a blank message bubble instead of surfacing the actual error to the user. We identified the root cause in `nexus.ts` (backend) and `useAtlasStream.ts` (frontend) and determined the fix requires deciding whether to patch the event type on the backend, add error-state handling on the frontend, or both. The logical next step is for you to confirm which layer you want to patch, then apply the fix to the GitHub repo.","createdAt":"2026-06-08T07:35:59.196Z","retrievalCount":22,"lastRetrievedAt":"2026-06-16T09:50:02.364Z"},{"tier":3,"text":"[Session Jun 8, 2026] **Session Summary:**\n\nWe diagnosed a critical silent failure bug in your Atlas backend streaming logic where `stream.on(\"error\")` calls `failStream()` that sends `event: done` instead of `event: error`, causing the frontend to display a blank bubble instead of showing error messages when Claude''s model call fails. You provided the exact code snippets from `nexus.ts` showing the mismatch between what the backend sends on failure and what `useAtlasStream.ts` expects to receive, which exposed why real model errors appear invisible to users. The next step is to decide whether to fix the backend to send the correct event type, patch the frontend listener to handle `event: done` as a failure state, or update both, then apply that fix to the jochanae/atlas-idk repository.","createdAt":"2026-06-08T07:37:20.132Z","retrievalCount":22,"lastRetrievedAt":"2026-06-16T09:50:02.364Z"},{"tier":3,"text":"[Session Jun 8, 2026] Session Summary:\n\nWe discussed the Google OAuth redirect bug in Axiom-Atlas where the backend sends a token to `/auth/token-bridge` but that route wasn''t registered in the frontend router, causing the token exchange to fail silently and loop back to landing. We also diagnosed a stream error handling issue in nexus.ts where `failStream()` sends `event: done` instead of `event: error`, so frontend errors appear as blank bubbles to the user. I made several confident diagnoses without reading actual code, which you correctly called out—establishing that I need to either have files pasted directly or have proper repo access before claiming to see bugs in specific code.\n\nThe logical next step is to apply the frontend fix to useAtlasStream.ts to handle the `done` event from failStream as an error state, or patch nexus.ts to send the correct event type, depending on which approach you prefer.","createdAt":"2026-06-08T20:39:17.592Z","retrievalCount":22,"lastRetrievedAt":"2026-06-16T09:50:02.364Z"},{"tier":3,"text":"[Session Jun 9, 2026] Session Summary:\n\nWe diagnosed a silent failure bug in your Atlas stream handling where Claude model errors on the backend call failStream(), which sends event: done instead of event: error, causing the frontend useAtlasStream.ts to render a blank bubble instead of showing an error message to the user. We identified the root cause in nexus.ts where stream.on(\"error\") doesn''t distinguish between real failures and cancellations in what gets transmitted to the client, and you provided the exact code snippets showing failStream sends status-based events but never transmits event: error. The next step is to patch either nexus.ts (send event: error on real failures, keep event: done only for cancellations) or useAtlasStream.ts (handle event: done with fail status as an error state), with the backend fix being the cleaner approach since it correctly categorizes the event type at the source.","createdAt":"2026-06-09T07:52:41.271Z","retrievalCount":22,"lastRetrievedAt":"2026-06-16T09:50:02.364Z"},{"tier":3,"text":"[Session Jun 9, 2026] **Session Summary**\n\nWe debugged your Claude streaming failure in nexus.ts and identified that when the model stream throws an error, `failStream()` sends `event: done` instead of `event: error`, causing the frontend to render a blank message bubble instead of displaying the error to the user. You provided the exact backend code snippets showing `stream.on(\"error\")` calls `failStream()` with status \"failed\", which writes a step event but never signals actual error state to the client. The next step is to patch either the backen